@iu2  the director/writer moved to Canada when she was 5 years old.  Saying someone who spent all of the first 5 years of their life in Korea ia "Korean" culturally is a bit of a stretch. She's much more Canadian. Even if I were to grant she is culturally Korean, it is still made in a country where she is a minority, by a company from a country where she is a minority, for a public in which she is a minority.

Plus the other director was born in Idaho. The screenplay was by someone who was born in Mexico and someone born in a small US town.

It also isn't a Korean movie. It is an American-Canadian movie featuring Korean themes. Hollywood making a movie set in Germany does not make it a German movie. An US-Canadian company making a movie set in Korea does not make it a Korean movie. At best it is a movie about Korea.

@TwistyMcFisty Amazon's mistake in the case of New World wasn't to try to make it appeal to a wider audience, it was to blow way too much money on a minuscule niche in the first place.
Seriously, if you want to make a full loot pvp MMO, make something low budget because the amount of people willing to play that kind of game isn't big enough to warrant a bigger budget. Unless your goal is to lose money, of course.
Albion Online understood that and it does well enough to keep going, as far as I know.

@mmach8 I see your point of view. Shame can be debilitating and I would absolutely agree that a movie that successfully teaches one to not let shame prevent them from succeeding could be a really good one.

As a parent, you should always use due diligence with regard to what your child is viewing. My point is that this film normalizes the acceptance of demonology (if at a cartoon-like level) and lazily uses a popular genre (Korean pop) to do so. It's less a matter of "will this cause immediate irreparable damage to my child" and more a "why am I giving this company my money to fill my kid's head with this".

I think it's a poor investment, but like you said, it's up to the parents' discretion. I just hope you choose wisely, wether it's this film, any other film on CriticalDrinker's channel, or whatever you have available. Evaluate the message you are uncomfortable with, because your child might pick it up.

@KatallinaVT But didn't she have the patterns from birth?  Your explanation makes sense other than that point.  If they're some sort of inherited shame then she had them regardless of how she felt and the end of the movie implies that she just shouldn't have ever felt bad about them (it was society that made her).  But if that's the case then there's nothing particularly wrong with partnering with demons, which means they aren't inherently evil, which means the girls were slaughtering these things throughout the movie which were ultimately just being controlled by a greater evil.

"Imagine going your whole life, thinking you are inherently repugnant"

Isn't that exactly what the demons are doing, and why they're constantly suffering?  The only difference is that they don't have to hide anything because everyone around them accepts them, which seems to be the message the movie sends to Zoey.  They're just "bad" but are they any different from the protagonist in the end?
